According to tradition, during the {{ill|Usa Hachiman Shrine Oracle Incident|ja|宇佐八幡宮神託事件|12=draft}}, {{ill|Waki Kiyomaro|ja|和気清麻呂|12=draft}}—exiled to Ōsumi—visited the area, and it is said that the staff (杖) he carried was driven into the ground and took root (a legend known as the {{ill|Tsue Tate Densetsu|ja|杖立て伝説|12=draft}}). It is further recorded that by the 4th year of the {{ill|Hoan Era|ja|保安|12=draft}} (1123), when {{ill|Kamō Shunsei|ja|蒲生舜清|12=draft}} founded Kamō Hachiman Shrine, the tree was already venerated as a sacred tree ({{ill|Shinboku|ja|神木|12=draft}}), suggesting that it was already of considerable size at that time.<ref name="蒲生八幡神社">[http://www.kamou80000.com/okusu.html {{ill|Kamō Hachiman Shrine|ja|蒲生八幡神社|12=draft}} “Japan’s Largest Giant Tree”] (accessed October 16, 2021)</ref> In the 3rd year of the {{ill|Eishō Era|ja|永正|12=draft}} (1506), a fire broke out on January 7 in the forest of Hachiman, resulting in the burning of some branches.

In 1913 ({{ill|Taishō 2|ja|大正2nd year|12=draft}}), the tree was featured in the "Great Japanese Old Trees Ranking" as the Eastern Yokozuna, and on March 8 of Taishō 11 it was designated a {{ill|Natural Monument|ja|天然記念物|12=draft}}, and later, on March 29, 1952 ({{ill|Showa 27|ja|昭和27th year|12=draft}}), it was designated as a {{ill|Special Natural Monument|ja|特別天然記念物|12=draft}}. On August 31, 1985 (Showa 60), due to strong winds from {{ill|Typhoon No. 13 of Showa 60|ja|昭和60th year 台風第13号|12=draft}}, many branches and leaves were lost; however, through the protective efforts of local residents, the tree has recovered.

It is noted that another tree, the "Great Kus" of Izumi in {{ill|Izumi City|ja|出水市|12=draft}}, which is designated as a municipal natural monument, is considered a kindred tree to Kamō no Kus, and a tragic love legend is associated with the two.<ref name="蒲生八幡神社"/>

