{{Location map~|Japan Kagoshima Prefecture|lat=31.765764|long=130.569442|position=left|label='''Kamō no Kus'''|mark=Red pog.svg}}
{{Location map~|Japan Kagoshima Prefecture|lat=31.596806|long=130.557139|position=left|label=<small>{{ill|Kagoshima City|ja|鹿児島市|12=draft|12=draft}}</small>|mark=Green pog.svg}}
}}
The tree stands approximately 30 meters tall, with a trunk circumference of 24.2 meters measured at a height of 1.3 meters above ground level, and a root spread of 33.5 meters. An internal cavity measuring about 13 square meters (equivalent to eight tatami mats) has been detected within the trunk. Its age is estimated at around 1500 years (as of {{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|12=draft|12=draft}} 23 ({{ill|2011|ja|2011th year|12=draft|12=draft}})). A survey conducted by the {{ill|Environmental Agency|ja|環境庁|12=draft|12=draft}} in Showa 63 ({{ill|1988|ja|1988th year|12=draft|12=draft}}) recognized it as the largest giant tree in Japan. It is also sometimes referred to as "Kamō no Ōkus" (蒲生の大楠) or "Kamō no Ōkus" (蒲生の大クス).

== History ==
According to tradition, during the {{ill|Usa Hachiman Shrine Oracle Incident|ja|宇佐八幡宮神託事件|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Waki Kiyomaro|ja|和気清麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}}—exiled to Ōsumi—visited the area, and it is said that the staff (杖) he carried was driven into the ground and took root (a legend known as the {{ill|Tsue Tate Densetsu|ja|杖立て伝説|12=draft|12=draft}}). It is further recorded that by the 4th year of the {{ill|Hoan Era|ja|保安|12=draft|12=draft}} (1123), when {{ill|Kamō Shunsei|ja|蒲生舜清|12=draft|12=draft}} founded Kamō Hachiman Shrine, the tree was already venerated as a sacred tree ({{ill|Shinboku|ja|神木|12=draft|12=draft}}), suggesting that it was already of considerable size at that time.<ref name="蒲生八幡神社">[http://www.kamou80000.com/okusu.html {{ill|Kamō Hachiman Shrine|ja|蒲生八幡神社|12=draft|12=draft}} “Japan’s Largest Giant Tree”] (accessed October 16, 2021)</ref> In the 3rd year of the {{ill|Eishō Era|ja|永正|12=draft|12=draft}} (1506), a fire broke out on January 7 in the forest of Hachiman, resulting in the burning of some branches.

In 1913 ({{ill|Taishō 2|ja|大正2nd year|12=draft|12=draft}}), the tree was featured in the "Great Japanese Old Trees Ranking" as the Eastern Yokozuna, and on March 8 of Taishō 11 it was designated a {{ill|Natural Monument|ja|天然記念物|12=draft|12=draft}}, and later, on March 29, 1952 ({{ill|Showa 27|ja|昭和27th year|12=draft|12=draft}}), it was designated as a {{ill|Special Natural Monument|ja|特別天然記念物|12=draft|12=draft}}. On August 31, 1985 (Showa 60), due to strong winds from {{ill|Typhoon No. 13 of Showa 60|ja|昭和60th year 台風第13号|12=draft|12=draft}}, many branches and leaves were lost; however, through the protective efforts of local residents, the tree has recovered.

It is noted that another tree, the "Great Kus" of Izumi in {{ill|Izumi City|ja|出水市|12=draft|12=draft}}, which is designated as a municipal natural monument, is considered a kindred tree to Kamō no Kus, and a tragic love legend is associated with the two.<ref name="蒲生八幡神社"/>

